Section X: Security, Conduct, and Responsibilities – Kahana

1. Purpose
This section explains Kahana’s expectations for behavior, security, and compliance. All employees and contractors must follow these requirements to help protect Kahana Oasis, our customers, and company assets.

2. Code of Conduct
Employees must:

Act with honesty, integrity, and respect toward colleagues, customers, and partners.

Follow all company policies (security, acceptable use, anti‑harassment, etc.).
​

Report suspected misconduct or policy violations to a manager, HR, or Security.

Harassment, discrimination, retaliation, and other inappropriate behavior are not tolerated and may result in disciplinary action, up to and including termination.

3. Security Responsibilities (Everyone)
Every employee is responsible for security, not just the Security team.

You must:

Protect accounts with strong passwords and multi‑factor authentication where required.

Never share passwords or authentication tokens.

Lock your screen and secure your devices when away from your desk.

Use company‑approved tools for work data; do not store work data in personal cloud or email.

Be cautious with links and attachments; report phishing or suspicious messages.

Immediately report lost/stolen devices, suspected account compromise, or potential data exposure.

Failure to follow security policies can lead to disciplinary action and may be considered a serious performance issue.

4. Acceptable Use of Systems
When using Kahana devices, accounts, and networks you must:

Use them primarily for legitimate business purposes.

Avoid illegal, abusive, or inappropriate content and activities.

Not install unapproved or pirated software.

Not attempt to bypass security controls, hack systems, or access data you are not authorized to see.

These expectations complement the detailed Acceptable Use Policy and Workstation Security Policy you have already created.

5. Confidentiality and Data Handling
Employees must:

Treat all non‑public Kahana and customer information as at least Internal or Confidential, and follow the Data Classification and Data Retention policies.

Only access and use data needed to perform their job (“need‑to‑know”).

Not disclose confidential information outside Kahana unless explicitly authorized and under appropriate agreements (e.g., NDA).

Obligations to protect confidential information continue even after employment ends.

6. Onboarding, Training, and Acknowledgment
New hires receive an overview of key security and compliance policies during onboarding, including Acceptable Use, Access Control, Password, Incident Reporting, and this Handbook section.

All employees must complete required security awareness training at least annually.

Employees must acknowledge in writing (e.g., e‑signature) that they have received, read, and agree to follow the Employee Handbook and security policies; updated versions will be communicated and may require re‑acknowledgment.

7. Reporting Concerns
Kahana encourages employees to report:

Suspected security incidents (phishing, data leakage, lost devices).

Policy violations or unethical behavior.

Reports can be made to your manager, HR, Security, or via any designated reporting channel. Good‑faith reporting is protected; retaliation is prohibited.

